         <ref id="ref2">
            <label>2.</label>
            <mixed-citation>For lack of space, a full and in-depth analysis of several novels by Sow Fall cannot be conducted here.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref3">
            <label>3.</label>
            <mixed-citation>According to Diagne, one must reject the arraignment of reason by Western logocentricism, cast in this historico-philosophical hypothesis as a form of<source>
                  <italic>pensée unique</italic>
               </source>and open it to traditional speech (<fpage>5</fpage>–<lpage>10</lpage>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref4">
            <label>4.</label>
            <mixed-citation>Some critics believe that<article-title>“qu'à côté des méthodes inspirées de l'Occident, il y a une voie propre à l'Afrique”</article-title>(<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Mateso</string-name>
               </person-group>
               <fpage>295</fpage>) ‘next to Western-inspired methods, there is a specifically African way of reading texts.’</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref5">
            <label>5.</label>
            <mixed-citation>This corpus is comprised of<source>
                  <italic>Le Revenant</italic>
               </source>(<year>1976</year>),<source>
                  <italic>La Grève des Bàttu</italic>
               </source>(<year>1979</year>),<source>
                  <italic>L'Appel des arènes</italic>
               </source>(<year>1982</year>),<source>
                  <italic>L'Ex-père de la nation</italic>
               </source>(<year>1987</year>), and<source>
                  <italic>Le Jujubier du patriarche</italic>
               </source>(<year>1993</year>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref6">
            <label>6.</label>
            <mixed-citation>According to<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Amadou Koné</string-name>
               </person-group>,<article-title>“la spécificité du discours romanesque, c'est qu'ilest traversé de ‘discours étrangers’ à l'intérieur d'un même langage”</article-title>(<fpage>61</fpage>) ‘the specificity of a narrative discourse is that it is shot through with foreign discourses coexisting within a single language.’</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref7">
            <label>7.</label>
            <mixed-citation>By this I mean any narrative, story, fable, or anecdote that takes up thematic, structural, and aesthetic features associated with traditional literature (see<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Ivor Case</string-name>
               </person-group>
               <fpage>51</fpage>). However, it is worth pointing out that the oralization of language is not a preserve of francophone novelists, although most if not all of them draw on this literary technique (<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Dérive</string-name>
               </person-group>
               <fpage>196</fpage>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref8">
            <label>8.</label>
            <mixed-citation>The opening finale, otherwise known as the dialectic of the folktale, is a narrative procedure widely used in black Africa. It consists of stating, in the opening of the tale, or by way of conclusion, observations that, in an abbreviated form and in proverbial garb, recapitulate where the narrative has been—or will be—the expanded form, the “unfolding” (<italic>explicare</italic>). See<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Diagne</string-name>
               </person-group>,<article-title>“Civilisation”</article-title>
               <fpage>15</fpage>.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref9">
            <label>9.</label>
            <mixed-citation>According to the Wolof ethical code, those who feel insecure and at a disadvantage in their relationship with others, those who fail to understand correctly what true and legitimate dignity is all about, are the ones who believe they must put on a facade, thus allowing themselves to be led down the path of irrational conducts under the pretense that their honor is at stake. See<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Sylla</string-name>
               </person-group>
               <fpage>177</fpage>.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref10">
            <label>10.</label>
            <mixed-citation>
               <article-title>“In Africa it is anthropologically verifiable that, generally, the operative ethic is communalism”</article-title>(<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Wiredu</string-name>
               </person-group>
               <fpage>15</fpage>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref11">
            <label>11.</label>
            <mixed-citation>Goldenstein insists on the fact that the transition from<italic>hors-texte</italic>to<italic>texte</italic>is effected through the agency of a certain number of<italic>topoï</italic>, including that of light, which deploys a rhetoric of unveiling by revealing a character, a textual space, etc. (<fpage>75</fpage>–<lpage>77</lpage>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref12">
            <label>12.</label>
            <mixed-citation>See also<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Greimas</string-name>
               </person-group>
               <fpage>180</fpage>.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref13">
            <label>13.</label>
            <mixed-citation>Although embodied by different characters, both positive and negative heroes must be seen as the two complementary sides of any human being (<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Paulme</string-name>
               </person-group>
               <fpage>150</fpage>–<lpage>51</lpage>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref14">
            <label>14.</label>
            <mixed-citation>
               <person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Jean Dérive</string-name>
               </person-group>explains this salient formal feature of non-metropolitan francophone literary production by pointing out that next to the—often privileged—thematization of highly sensitive cultural issues, style was also an essential vector through which claims about difference were articulated (<fpage>191</fpage>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref15">
            <label>15.</label>
            <mixed-citation>According to Pape Samba Diop, this type of borrowing does not fundamentally modify the primary framework of storytelling, i.e., diegetic configuration, as theorized by Genette (<fpage>80</fpage>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref16">
            <label>16.</label>
            <mixed-citation>According to Jean-François Durand, the song, as Sow Fall reconstitutes it in the novel, is not based on any particular epic, but is instead an attempt to paint a syncretic picture of the African past—albeit the latter is reduced to the Fulani of the Foudjallon (<fpage>95</fpage>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
